# ACT ONE

[[Director's note: Act One establishes the geography — both physical
and psychological. Every location in this act has a double meaning.
The village is also a mind. The roads are also memory.]]

================================================================================
                ELEMENT: Forced Scene Heading — dot prefix
================================================================================

.VILLAGE OF ARDMOR — THE ROAD IN — DAY

= The cartographer arrives. Not returning. She has never been here. She knows this place completely.

The road narrows as it enters the village. Ancient stone walls crowd
close. The light arrives here differently — later than elsewhere,
staying longer. As if reluctant.

ELENA MARSH (40s) stops her car where the road ends.

She gets out. Studies the village square with the focused neutrality
of someone reading a text in a language they pretend not to speak.

She opens a leather case. Inside: hand-drawn maps. Old. Precise.
Obsessively so.

She looks at the nearest building. Looks at the map. The building
is not on the map.

Neither is the road she just drove in on.

================================================================================
                ELEMENT: Standard Scene Heading
================================================================================

INT. VILLAGE INN — DAY

= Elena tries to establish herself in a place that has already decided who she is.

Low ceilings. A fire despite the mild day. BRIGID (70s, proprietor,
the kind of woman who has absorbed so much history she radiates it)
watches Elena set her case on the counter.

BRIGID
You're the one who wrote about the
Corlan Valley route.

ELENA
(not a question to her)
You've read my work.

BRIGID
My husband used your maps when the
roads flooded. Three years ago.
He found a way through that no one
else knew existed.

A pause. Elena looks at the fire.

ELENA
How is he now?

Brigid's hands stop their movement.

BRIGID
He didn't make it back.

The fire moves. The room doesn't.

ELENA
I'm sorry.

BRIGID
Don't be.
(beat)
He found the way through. That
mattered to him. You gave him that.

She sets a room key on the counter. The conversation is closed.
Not coldly. Definitively.

================================================================================
                ELEMENT: Centered text — for transitions, title cards, lyrics
================================================================================

>Three days later.<

> — <

INT. VILLAGE INN — ELENA'S ROOM — NIGHT

The maps cover every surface. All of them wrong.

Not wrong in the way of error. Wrong in the way of a map that
charts a place that has been deliberately changed.

Elena holds two maps side by side. Same road. Same name. Different
course.

================================================================================
                ELEMENT: Section heading — sub-act / sequence level
================================================================================

## The First Road

INT. VILLAGE INN — ELENA'S ROOM — NIGHT

A knock at the door. Elena doesn't move. Waits.

The knock again. Different rhythm. Patient.

ELENA
It's open.

CORMAC (30s, the local schoolteacher — you can tell by the chalk
dust he's stopped noticing and the books that live in every pocket)
enters. He has something to say that he has rehearsed and is now
abandoning.

CORMAC
I heard you're mapping the old routes.

ELENA
That's what I do.

CORMAC
There are routes here that aren't
supposed to be mapped.

ELENA
Those are the only ones worth finding.

Cormac looks at the maps spread across the floor. He is reading
them the way a person reads something that concerns them.

CORMAC
My father made those.

[[Elena's reaction here should be minimal — what we track is the
stillness that enters her body. The understanding that something
she thought was research has become, unexpectedly, personal.]]

================================================================================
                ELEMENT: Fountain Bold and Italic in action lines
================================================================================

She picks up one of the maps with both hands. Studies it.

The lines are precise. The handwriting in the margins is *identical*
to the handwriting in her father's letters.

She sets the map down without speaking.

_This is what it means to find what you were not looking for._

================================================================================
                ELEMENT: Section — scene-level
================================================================================

### The Map That Shouldn't Exist

EXT. MOORLAND — NORTH OF THE VILLAGE — DAWN

= The road the maps all end at. And what lies beyond it.

No path visible. Elena walks anyway. She has a compass she doesn't
use. She trusts something else — the specific quality of attention
that has guided her across four continents and seven years of
professional solitude.

Cormac follows. He keeps a respectful distance. He is learning her
pace.

They walk for twenty minutes without speaking. The moor absorbs
sound. By the time they are half a mile out, the village behind
them could be a painting.

Elena stops.

In front of her: a road. Perfectly maintained. Not on any map.
Lined on both sides by low stone walls that have been here long
enough to have opinions.

CORMAC
(very quietly)
No one comes up here.

ELENA
Your father did.

She takes out his map. Places her finger at the exact point where
the road on the map ends.

She is standing on it.

The road continues.

The map does not.

================================================================================
                ELEMENT: Page break (=== triple equals, standalone)
================================================================================

===

# ACT TWO

## What the Road Knows

= Elena follows the unmapped road. Cormac follows Elena. What they find
  changes what both of them thought they were looking for.

EXT. UNMAPPED ROAD — DAY

The road leads them to a valley that appears on no survey. From
this height, looking down, it is strangely beautiful — green in
the specific shade of things that have been left alone for a long
time.

In the valley: a house. Smoke from the chimney. Someone is home.

Elena and Cormac stand at the crest without speaking.

What they are each thinking is different. What they are each
feeling is not.

================================================================================
                ELEMENT: Dual dialogue — ^ caret marks simultaneous speech
================================================================================

ELENA                                      ^CORMAC
We should go down.                         ^We shouldn't go down.

They look at each other.

A beat. Then Elena starts walking down.

Cormac watches her go.

CORMAC
(to himself, and to the valley, and
to whatever his father left here)
She's going to change everything.

He follows.

================================================================================
                ELEMENT: Lyrics — ~ tilde prefix for sung text
================================================================================

INT. THE VALLEY HOUSE — MAIN ROOM — DAY

The house has been lived in with intention. Books. Maps — different
ones, older ones. A woman's voice from the back room:

~  I mapped the road that leads to you
~  I mapped the field and mapped the view
~  I could not map the way I feel
~  Some roads cannot become real

The singing stops. A long silence.

Then MARA (80s, Elena's father's handwriting alive in her face)
appears in the doorway. She looks at Elena with the specific
expression of someone who has been waiting for a particular person
for a very particular number of years.

MARA
You found it.

ELENA
I followed the road.

MARA
Your father built that road.
So that you would.

===

# ACT THREE

## The Map That Was Always for You

= Elena learns why the road was hidden. Cormac learns why his father
  made the maps. The truth is not what either of them expected, and
  it is better.

[[Note: Act Three should move quickly. The mystery has resolved.
What remains is the emotional reckoning, and that requires
precision, not elaboration. Trust the audience to carry the weight
they've been given.]]

INT. THE VALLEY HOUSE — MAIN ROOM — LATER

Mara spreads a map across the table. The original. Every road in
the county. Every route. And in the center, where the valley is:
a blank space, deliberate, surrounded by a hand-drawn border.

MARA
He left it blank so that whoever
followed the road would fill it in
themselves. So the map would be theirs.

Elena looks at the blank space.

She takes out her pen.

CORMAC
(gently)
You don't have to do it now.

ELENA
Yes. I do.

She begins to draw. Her hand is completely steady. Her face is
something that cannot be named in the forward direction, only
recognized in retrospect.

She draws the road. The valley. The house.

She draws a small mark at the place where she is standing.

Here.

I am here.

MARA
(watching)
He said you'd know what to draw.

ELENA
(not stopping)
He taught me everything I know
about roads that shouldn't exist.

She draws the last line. Sets down the pen.

The map is complete.

Outside, through the window, the road leads back to the village.
And from here, looking back, it is visible for the first time.

It was always there.

>FADE OUT.<

