DOCUMENT STRUCTURE:
  Title:            Document title (title page)
  Author:           Writer name (title page)
  Draft date:       Version date (title page)
  Credit:           "Written by", "Story by", etc. (title page)
  Source:           Adapted from / Original (title page)
  Copyright:        Year (title page)
  Contact:          Representation info (title page)
  Notes:            Production or draft notes (title page)

SCENE HEADINGS:
  Standard:         INT./EXT. LOCATION — TIME
  Forced:           .HEADING TEXT (dot prefix forces any line to heading)
  Subheadings:      The line after a heading with "—" is the sub-location

SECTIONS (structural navigation, not rendered in final output):
  # Primary section (Act level)
  ## Secondary section (Sequence level)
  ### Tertiary section (Scene/beat level)

SYNOPSES (story outline, follows heading, not rendered in output):
  = One line synopsis of the scene or section

NOTES (writer annotations, not rendered in output):
  [[Single note or annotation here]]

BONEYARD (multi-line comment, never rendered):
  /* All content here is invisible in output */

PAGE BREAK (forced page break in output):
  === (triple equals on its own line)

TEXT STYLING (in action lines):
  *bold text*                   Bold
  _italic text_                 Italic
  _*bold italic*_               Bold and italic
  \*escaped asterisk            Literal asterisk, not bold

CENTERED TEXT (transitions, title cards):
  >TEXT HERE<                   Centered on the page

DUAL DIALOGUE (simultaneous speech):
  CHARACTER A                   ^CHARACTER B
  First dialogue                ^Second dialogue

LYRICS (sung text):
  ~ First sung line
  ~ Second sung line

CHARACTER EXTENSIONS:
  CHARACTER NAME (V.O.)         Voice over
  CHARACTER NAME (O.S.)         Off screen
  CHARACTER NAME (CONT'D)       Continued after action
  CHARACTER NAME (PRE-LAP)      Voice heard before cut
  CHARACTER NAME (ON PHONE)     Phone conversation

CRAFT PRINCIPLES DEMONSTRATED:
  — The synopsis (=) tells; the scene shows
  — Notes [[]] for director or self — removed from production draft
  — Section headers (#) for writer navigation, invisible to cast
  — Boneyard for deleted material worth keeping as reference
  — Centered text (>...<) for moments that require visual centering
  — Physical action carries what dialogue cannot
  — The map as metaphor for the story about maps — form serves content
